          <h2>6 Document Problems That Cause Rejections</h2>

          <h3>1. Missing Documents</h3>

          <p>
            The most frequent rejection cause. MOHRE requires a specific set of documents per occupation category. Missing even one triggers the Nawakas process. Common omissions:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Academic certificates (degree, diploma, or professional qualification)</li>
            <li>Experience letters from previous employers</li>
            <li>Professional licenses for regulated occupations (healthcare, engineering, education)</li>
            <li>Medical fitness certificate</li>
            <li>Passport-size photographs (white background)</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>2. Expired Passports or Visas</h3>

          <p>
            The Eye system blocks these automatically:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Passport:</strong> Must be valid for at least 6 months beyond the application date</li>
            <li><strong>Existing visa:</strong> Must have at least 1 month remaining</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            If your passport expires within 6 months, renew it before starting the work permit process. Renewing after submission means restarting the application.
          </p>

          <h3>3. Unclear or Unattested Academic Certificates</h3>

          <p>
            Your <a href="/blog/degree-certificate-translation-dubai/">degree certificate</a> needs to be properly attested before MOHRE accepts it. The <a href="/blog/uae-attestation-process-guide/">attestation chain</a> depends on your home country's Hague Convention status:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hague countries</strong> (India, UK, USA, Philippines, Bangladesh, Canada): Notarization, then apostille, then MOJ-certified Arabic translation</li>
            <li><strong>Non-Hague countries</strong> (Pakistan, Egypt): Notarization, home MOFA, UAE Embassy, UAE MOFA, then MOJ-certified Arabic translation</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            The UAE is <strong>not a Hague Convention member</strong>. This fact does not change the requirement for incoming documents, which still follow the Hague/non-Hague pathway based on the issuing country.
          </p>

          <h3>4. Job Offer Contradictions</h3>

          <p>
            MOHRE checks that your job offer aligns with UAE labor law. Issues that trigger rejection:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Job title does not match your qualifications</li>
            <li>Salary below minimum thresholds for the occupation</li>
            <li>Occupation code does not match the employer's trade license activities</li>
            <li>Contract terms violating Federal Decree-Law No. 33 of 2021 (UAE Labour Law)</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            These are employer-side issues. If your work permit is rejected for job offer reasons, your employer's PRO needs to correct the application.
          </p>

          <h3>5. Company Violations or Quota Issues</h3>

          <p>
            Sometimes the rejection has nothing to do with your documents. MOHRE blocks new work permits when:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>The employer has outstanding labor violations</li>
            <li>The company has exceeded its Emiratisation quota</li>
            <li>The employer's trade license is expired or suspended</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            Your employer must resolve these issues before resubmitting. There is nothing an employee can fix on their end for these rejections.
          </p>

